<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/TSAHTP">
<title>Tsai, Cheng-Hung: How to Prove Wisdom Exists</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/TSAHTP</link>
<description>_Analysis_. forthcomingThe aim of this paper is to argue that practical wisdom, like any other genuine system in the world, does exist. According to practical wisdom eliminativism, there is no such thing as practical wisdom, or, as Christian Miller has put it, on metaphysical grounds, practical wisdom does not exist. This paper develops an argument, termed the System Argument, which specifies the conditions under which practical wisdom exists and establishes its existence. It further contrasts the System Response, represented by the System Argument, with the Analogy Response, which seeks to demonstrate the existence of practical wisdom through analogies such as the decathlon and enology. This comparison demonstrates the greater explanatory power of the System Argument.&#x3C;div&#x3E;(&#x3C;a href=&#x22;https://philpapers.org/go.pl?id=TSAHTP&#x26;amp;proxyId=&#x26;amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1093%2Fanalys%2Fanag038&#x22;&#x3E;direct link&#x3C;/a&#x3E;)&#x3C;/div&#x3E;</description>
<taxo:topics>
  <rdf:Bag>
  </rdf:Bag>
</taxo:topics>
</item>
<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/HEBVGA">
<title>Hebbink, Nick ; Schinkel, Anders &#x26; de Ruyter, Doret: Virtuous gratitude as an aim of education</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/HEBVGA</link>
<description>_Journal of Moral Education_:1-16. 2026This article justifies virtuous gratitude as an aim of formal education. This virtue is characterised by the disposition to perceive, think, feel and act in accordance with the moral ideal of acknowledging and cherishing the gratuitous good in life. At its heart lies a conscientious commitment to this ideal, infused with a concern for truth, justice and wellbeing. This virtue also requires guidance by wisdom, and a capacity for reflective awareness and imagination. We map risks accompanying misguided gratitude and the shortcomings that must be overcome to avoid them. We demonstrate why this virtue is both conducive to and constitutive of flourishing&#x2014;an important overarching aim of education. Virtuous gratitude can deepen people&#x2019;s outlook and promote ongoing self-cultivation and wisdom. Thus, fostering this virtue not only necessitates education but contributes to it. We conclude that virtuous gratitude is not merely a legitimate aim, but a required aim of formal education.&#x3C;div&#x3E;(&#x3C;a href=&#x22;https://philpapers.org/go.pl?id=HEBVGA&#x26;amp;proxyId=&#x26;amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.tandfonline.com%2Fdoi%2Ffull%2F10.1080%2F03057240.2026.2675412&#x22;&#x3E;direct link&#x3C;/a&#x3E;)&#x3C;/div&#x3E;</description>
<taxo:topics>
  <rdf:Bag>
  </rdf:Bag>
</taxo:topics>
</item>
