<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/SWAPFW">
<title>Swartwood, Jason D.: Practice for Wisdom: On the Neglected Role of Case-Based Critical Reflection</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/SWAPFW</link>
<description>_Topoi_ 43 (3):1-13. 2024Despite increased philosophical and psychological work on practical wisdom, contemporary interdisciplinary wisdom research provides few specifics about how to develop wisdom (Kristj&#xE1;nsson 2022). This lack of practically useful guidance is due in part to the difficulty of determining how to combine the tools of philosophy and psychology to develop a plausible account of wisdom as a prescriptive ideal. Modeling wisdom on more ordinary forms of expertise is promising, but skill models of wisdom (Annas 2011; De Caro et al. 2018; Swartwood 2013b; Tsai 2023) have been challenged on the grounds that there are important differences between wisdom and expert skills (Hacker-Wright 2015, p. 986; Kristj&#xE1;nsson 2015, pp. 98, 101; Stichter 2015, 2016, 2018). I&#x2019;ll argue that we can both vindicate the promise of skill models of wisdom and begin to specify practically useful strategies for wisdom development by attending to a reflective process that I call Case-Based Critical Reflection. I begin by demonstrating the process as it arose in a notable example from everyday life, illustrating how the process can be usefully applied to a case study of interest to wisdom scientists, and explaining its philosophical pedigree. After isolating the key features that make it relevant to wisdom development, I argue that attending to the importance of Critical Reflection can defuse prominent objections to skill models of wisdom.&#x3C;div&#x3E;(&#x3C;a href=&#x22;https://philpapers.org/go.pl?id=SWAPFW&#x26;amp;proxyId=&#x26;amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Flink.springer.com%2Fepdf%2F10.1007%2Fs11245-023-10000-z%3Fsharing_token%3DpGymRWYqPkBuVRD2mlnVcve4RwlQNchNByi7wbcMAY6o12-D-xa2Js3dYBSRhQMb6cc-v5sZqpFiyubUrwg7O2hMWXBQbM8FTfB-Bv5lZ9ElX-BXsSEaFJ3bLIMhjAM5e3DShdF5JYDpnqpxurlI1m7SbftsL8bP5J0JGFMlnvU%253D&#x22;&#x3E;direct link&#x3C;/a&#x3E;)&#x3C;/div&#x3E;</description>
