<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/DORVKA">
<title>Dorter, Kenneth: Virtue, Knowledge, and Wisdom: Bypassing Self-Control</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/DORVKA</link>
<description>_Review of Metaphysics_ 51 (2):313-343. 1997SOCRATES&#x2019; CLAIM THAT VIRTUE IS KNOWLEDGE implies that if we behave in an unvirtuous way we must be ignorant of what goodness really is. No allowance is made for the possibility that we may know what is good but act otherwise because we are too weak to resist temptation or fear&#x2014;in other words that we may lack self-mastery. In a famous passage Aristotle rejects the Socratic model.&#x3C;div&#x3E;(&#x3C;a href=&#x22;https://philpapers.org/go.pl?id=DORVKA&#x26;amp;proxyId=&#x26;amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pdcnet.org%2Fcollection%2Fshow%3Fid%3Drevmetaph_1997_51_2_0313_0344%26file_type%3Dpdf&#x22;&#x3E;direct link&#x3C;/a&#x3E;)&#x3C;/div&#x3E;</description>
