<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/BROOBO-3">
<title>Brown, Charles S.: Overcoming Boundaries of Wisdom: From Eco-Phenomenology to Eco-logos</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/BROOBO-3</link>
<description>_Dialogue and Universalism_ 15 (1-2):9-18. 2005This paper explores the contribution that a Husserlian inspired phenomenology can make to environmental philosophy. In particular I argue that Husserl&#x2019;s phenomenological critique of naturalism liberates thinking from its metaphysical na&#xEF;vet&#xE9; thereby opening thought to a new conception of nature, while his theory of intentionality can be adapted to provide new directions for developing an account of axiological rationality which is open to claim that there is goodness and value within non-human nature. Such a form of rationality, based in the dialectic of empty and filled intentions, would begin to provide a discourse in which the goodness and value of non-human nature could be registered, expressed, and articulated in a rational manner. The result will be an experiential grounding for environmental ethics.&#x3C;div&#x3E;(&#x3C;a href=&#x22;https://philpapers.org/go.pl?id=BROOBO-3&#x26;amp;proxyId=&#x26;amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pdcnet.org%2Fcollection%2Fshow%3Fid%3Ddu_2005_0015_41276_0009_0018%26file_type%3Dpdf&#x22;&#x3E;direct link&#x3C;/a&#x3E;)&#x3C;/div&#x3E;</description>
