<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/BENWIP-2">
<title>Benedikt, Amelie Frost: Wisdom in Philosophy: An Inquiry and Some Proposals</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/BENWIP-2</link>
<description>Philosophy means &#x22;the love of wisdom.&#x22; But what is &#x22;wisdom?&#x22; In order to answer and organize my discussion of this subject, I focus on responding to two more specific questions; one epistemological and one ethical. ;The first, epistemological question concerns what the wise know. It asks whether wisdom is more appropriately classified as a variety of knowledge, or whether wisdom is distinct from knowledge. It is based on a exploration of Plato&#x27;s changing view concerning the relationship between knowledge and wisdom and their relative potential for achieving certainty. My discussion of the epistemological question leads to an examination of dialectic in which I argue that the dialectical method is the fundamental source of disagreement among philosophers concerning the possibility for certainty due to its practice of first establishing, then refuting, knowledge claims. ;The second, ethical question concerns how the wise act. I examine the question by examining the historical debate concerning whether wisdom is a contemplative virtue, sophia, or an active virtue, phronesis. I propose that these views can be reconciled through the Greek idea of kairos. Kairos, or &#x22;opportune moment,&#x22; describes a special sense for &#x22;good timing,&#x22; a sense that I argue is not merely rhetorical but ethical. I argue for the idea that developing a sense of kairos can inform one when and whether to move between the reflective life devoted to cultivating sophia and the active life devoted to cultivating phronesis. I argue that the love of wisdom requires one to cultivate both these virtues and also to cultivate the sense of kairos needed to judge the right time to think and the right time to take action. ;I conclude by bringing together my conclusions from Part One and Part Two. In sum, I propose that wisdom is a kairic movement between sophia and phronesis based on a dialectical response to uncertainty.</description>
