  </rdf:Bag>
</taxo:topics>
</item>
<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/MORTAI-3">
<title>Morris, Michael John: Towards an Integrative Concept of Wisdom: A Factor Analytic Study</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/MORTAI-3</link>
<description>This study sought to define and conceptualize the variables that comprise wisdom. Eight variables were extracted from the literature which were thought to comprise wisdom. These variables were: confidence, empathy, humble, insight, knowledge, love, understanding, and a belief in God, Supreme being or single life force. ;Fourteen additional items suggested by other researchers were added to the study&#x27;s survey in order to provide a sufficient number of items to meet the criteria for reliability and validity. Surveys were evaluated. Two hundred and fifty-seven subjects were surveyed by random sampling procedures. All subjects were from central California or central Texas. Surveys also were grouped by age with the younger groups ranging between 18-35 years, the middle groups ranging between 36 and 64 years, and the older group being persons 65 plus years of age. ;A principal component factor analysis with varimax rotation revealed five factors for wisdom. The results showed that all eight variables predicted by the literature loaded on the first three factors. Nine of the additional items on the survey loaded on the five factors with five of these loading on the first three factors. ;The results which were obtained for wisdom also were compared to the concepts of good and altruism. In addition, the relationships of subjects&#x27; ages and their perception of the applicability of the variables to wisdom were studied. Although it was predicted that persons of older age would be more likely to place greater emphasis on the eight target variables, a multivariate analysis of centroids revealed that it was the younger age group who selected the variable insight as the sole differentiation. ;In addition, correlation coefficients of older age showed significant low to moderate relationships with confidence, humble, insight, knowledge, love, and a belief in a God. There was no significant relationship between older age and empathy or understanding</description>
