<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/MONPSO">
<title>Montgomery, Anita Josephine: Phenomenological Study of Wisdom</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/MONPSO</link>
<description>The purpose of this dissertation research project is to explore the meaning and experience of wisdom for older adults using the phenomenological method of inquiry. Individual in-depth interviews were conducted with six participants. Participants were asked to describe wisdom in terms of the truth of their own life experiences. The participants were co-researchers engaged in a mutual process of searching and describing what is beyond the presuppositions and assumptions about wisdom. The phenomenological research method was applied in the analysis of participant interviews to identify elements to the participants experiences. ;Results of the project are reported in the form of a dialogue to emphasize the participatory nature of the project and allow readers to be co-researchers in an inquiry of wisdom. A picture of the experience of wisdom emerged from the participant interviews. The appearance of the picture of wisdom will be determined by each reader&#x27;s thoughtful reflection of the elements that emerged from the interviews. Readers are invited to reflect on each element of wisdom as described by the participants and draw their own unique picture of wisdom. ;The picture of the experience of wisdom that was revealed through this research project shows the consummatory nature of wisdom. The meaning of a wise choice is revealed by the perspective of time, so Time is the landscape of the picture of wisdom. The predominate figure in the landscape is Guidance reflecting the elements of knowledge, experience and moral principles that operates to show the way. Guidance is supported in the picture by Relationships. Relationships is accentuated by Compassion. ;The elements that emerge from a phenomenological study of wisdom may direct efforts at understanding the aging experience. The element of Time as the context for the lived experiences of wisdom, and experience as a guiding elements both reconcile with the association of wisdom with old age. Time and experience are two elements of wisdom that reflect the distinctive feature of an older person--life time. Time, and how it is experienced is a factor that may be useful to consider in developing theories of aging. ;The appendix contains a review and analysis of ten published phenomenological studies to illustrate how the theory and method of phenomenology are used in research</description>
