<item rdf:about="https://philpapers.org/rec/MIPAW">
<title>Mi&#x15B;, Andrzej: Philosophy and Wisdom</title>
<link>https://philpapers.org/rec/MIPAW</link>
<description>_Dialogue and Universalism_ 11 (7):33-44. 2001Philosophy is not supreme wisdom for everyone &#x2014; for some, the philosopher is the outright negation of the true sage. The copious protreptic literature, which encourages readers to philosophize, is accompanied by equally numerous aprotreptic periodicals &#x2014; criticizing the very idea of philosophy and negating the very concept, namely, that with the help of his intellect man can and should reach the truth and live according to it. All those views targeted against philosophy could be rejected by stating that they are addressed not so much at philosophy, but its degenerate, failed forms. It seems better to heed the advice of Nietzsche, who wrote that: &#x201C;There are certain opponents of philosophy, and it is useful to hear their opinions [...]&#x201D;. By listening to the charges formulated by the anti-philosophers, the philosopher may raise his own metaphilosophical consciousness a step higher; there is never too much of such consciousness &#x2014; at any rate, without it there will never come into being a philosophy that could be recognized as the embodiment of true wisdom.&#x3C;div&#x3E;(&#x3C;a href=&#x22;https://philpapers.org/go.pl?id=MIPAW&#x26;amp;proxyId=&#x26;amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Felibrary.ru%2Fitem.asp%3Fid%3D4224824&#x22;&#x3E;direct link&#x3C;/a&#x3E;)&#x3C;/div&#x3E;</description>
